window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2016>1>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2016","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : BINARY OPERATIONS","question":"A binary operation * is defined on the set R of real numbers by m * n = m + n + 2. Find the   identify element under the operation *","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Given that:  m * n = m + n + 2  For m, n \u2208R  Let c be the identity element under *  Then m *e = e*m = m  Thus m *e = m + e + 2 = m  e = m - m - 2  Then, e = -2","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2016>1>b","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2016","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : BINARY OPERATIONS","question":"A binary operation * is defined on the set R of real numbers by m * n = m + n + 2. Find the Inverse of n under the operation *.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Let n - 1 be the inverse of n under *.  Then n * n-1 = e  Thus n * n-1 = N + n - 1 + 2 = -2  n-1 = -2 - 2 - n  Hence, n-1 = -n - 4","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2016>2","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2016","type":"Theory","sub_label":"2","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : CO-ORDINATE GEOMETRY OF STRAIGHT LINES","question":"Given that (5, 2), (-4, k) and (2, 1) lie on a straight line, find the value of k.  (Leaving the answer in whole number -b)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Let m1 be the gradient between points (5, 2) and (2, 1).  Thenm1=y2-y1x2-x1  =1-22-5  =-1-3=13  Let m2 be the gradient between point (5, 2) and (-4k).  Thenm2=k-2-1-5=k-2-9  But gradient of a straight line is the same between any pair of point on the line.  i.e13=k-2-9  -9 = 3(k - 2)  -9 = 3k - 6  -3k = -6 + 9 = 3  \u2234k=3-3=-1","marks":"10","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2016>3>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2016","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : FUNCTIONS","question":"If f(x + 2) = 6x2 + 5x - 8, find f(5).    (Leaving the answer in whole number bc)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"First, equate f(x + 2) and f(5) to find the actual value of x that should be substituted in the function i.e   f(x + 2) = f(5)  x + 2 = 5  x = 5 - 2  x = 3  Hence, f(3) = 6(3)2 + 5(3) - 8 = 6 \u00d7 9 + 15 - 8 = 61","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2016>3>b","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2016","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : SURDS","question":"Express7&radic;2&nbsp;+3&radic;3&nbsp;4&radic;2&nbsp;-2&radic;3&nbsp;intheformp+q &radic;r&nbsp;,wherep,qandrarerationalnumbers.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Given:  7&radic;2&nbsp;+3&radic;3&nbsp;4&radic;2&nbsp;-2&radic;3&nbsp;=7&radic;2&nbsp;+3&radic;3&nbsp;4&radic;2&nbsp;-2&radic;3&nbsp;\u00d74&radic;2&nbsp;+2&radic;3&nbsp;4&radic;2&nbsp;+2&radic;3&nbsp;  =28 \u00d7 2 + 14 &radic;6&nbsp; + 12 &radic;6&nbsp; + 6 \u00d7 3 (4&radic;2&nbsp;)2 - (2 &radic;3&nbsp;)2  =56+26&radic;6&nbsp;+1816\u00d72-4\u00d73=74+26&radic;6&nbsp;32-12  =3710+1310&radic;6&nbsp;","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2016>4","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2016","type":"Theory","sub_label":"4","group":"","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : POLYNOMIAL FUNCTIONS","question":"When f(x) = 2x3 + mx2 + nx + 11 is divided by x2 + 5x + 1, the quotient is 2x - 5 and the remainder is 30x + 16. Find the values of m and n.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Using polynomial = Q \u00d7 D + R, Given that  Q = quotient  D = Divisor  the remainder  Thus, f(x) = (2x - 5)(x2 + 5x + 1) + (30x + 10)  f(x) = 2x3 + 102 + 2x - 5x3 - 25x - 5 + 30x + 16  = 2x3 + 5x2 + 7x + 11  m = 5, n = 7","marks":"10","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2016>5>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2016","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : PROBABILITY","question":"The probabilities that Ago, Sulley and Musa will gain admission to a certain university are 4/5 , 3/4 and 2/3 , respectively. Find the probability that none of them will gain admission.  (Leaving the answer in fraction q/p)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Let P(A), P(S), P(M) represent the probabilities that Ago, Survey and Musa respectively will gain admission to a certain university.  then,  P(A)=45,P(S)=34,P(M)=23  P(A')=45-1P(S)=34,P(M)=23  P(A')=1-45=15  P(S')=1-34=14  P(m')=1-23=13  From the parameters above, the probability that mone of them will gain admission is   Pr = P(A') \u00d7 P(S') \u00d7 P(M')  =15\u00d714\u00d713  =160","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2016>5>b","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2016","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : PROBABILITY","question":"The probabilities that Ago, Sulley and Musa will gain admission to a certain university are 4/5 , 3/4 and 2/3 , respectively. Find the probability that only Ago and Sulley will gain admission.    (Leaving the answer in fraction q/p)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Let P(A), P(S), P(M) represent the probabilities that Ago, Survey and Musa respectively will gain admission to a certain university.  then,  P(A)=45,P(S)=34,P(M)=23  P(A')=45-1P(S)=34,P(M)=23  P(A')=1-45=15  P(S')=1-34=14  P(m')=1-23=13  The probability that only Ago and Sulley will gain admission  = P(A) \u00d7 P(S) \u00d7 P(M')  =45\u00d734\u00d713  =15","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2016>6>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2016","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : STATISTICS","question":"The mean of the numbers 1, 4, k, (k + 4) and 11 is (k + 1). Calculate the value of k    (Leaving the answer in fraction q/p)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Given:  \u2211x = 1 + 4 + k + (k + 4) + 11 = 2k + 20  n = 5, x\u0305 = k + 1  Using mean,  x\u0305=\u2211xn  K+1=2k+205  5(k + 1) = 2k + 20  5k + 5 = 2k + 20  5k - 2k = 20 - 5  3k = 15  k=153","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2016>6>b","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2016","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : STATISTICS","question":"The mean of the numbers 1, 4, k, (k + 4) and 11 is (k + 1). Calculate the standard deviation.    (Leaving the answer in two decimal place)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Given the table below:  x = 5 + 1 = 6  xd = x - x\u0305d21  4  5  9  11-5  -2  -1  3  525  4  1  9  25*sun*d2 = 64  Hence,standarddeviation=&radic;\u2211d2n&nbsp;  =&radic;645&nbsp; = &radic;12.8&nbsp; = 3.58","marks":"5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2016>7>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2016","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : THE IMPULSE AND MOMENTUM EQUATIONS","question":"A body of mass 3kg moves with a velocity of 8ms-1. It collides with a second body moving in the same direction with a velocity of 5ms-1. After collision the bodies move together with a velocity of 6ms-1. Find the mass of the second body.  (Leaving the answer in two decimal place)","images":["data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Given the illustration below  Before collision    After collision    By the principle of conservation of linear   m1u1 + m2u2 = m1v + m2v  3 \u00d7 8 + m2 \u00d7 5 = 3 \u00d7 6 + m2 \u00d7 6  24 + 5m2 = 18 + 6m2  24 - 18 = 6m2 - 5m2  6 = m2  \u2234 m2 = 6kg  Hence, mass of the second body is 6kg  b. Before collision     After collision    b. By the principle of conservation of linear momentum,  m1u1 + m2u2 = m1v + m2v  3 \u00d7 8 + 6 \u00d7 -5 = 3v + 6v  24 - 30 = 9v  -6 = 9v  v=-69 = 0.67ms-1  Hence, the two bodies move together with a common velocity of 0.67ms-1 in the direction of the second body of mass m2.","marks":"10","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2016>8","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2016","type":"Theory","sub_label":"8","group":"","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : VECTORS","question":"P = 5I + 3j, q = -i + 2j  r = 17i + 5j  r = \u03b1p + \u03b2q","images":[],"marking_scheme":"given parameters:  17i + 5j = \u03b1(5i + 3j) + \u03b2(-1 + 2j)  5\u03b1i + 3\u03b1j - \u03b2i + 2\u03b2j  (5\u03b1 - \u03b2) + (3\u03b1 + 2 \u03b2)j  Thus 17i + 5j = (5\u03b1 - \u03b2)i + (3\u03b1 + 2\u03b2)j  By comparison,  5\u03b1 - \u03b2 = 17 ------------- (1)  3\u03b1 + 2\u03b2 = 5 ----------- (2)  3 \u00d7 (1): 15\u03b1 - 3\u03b2 = 5I ----------------- (3)  5 \u00d7 (2) : 15\u03b1 + 10\u03b2 = 25 ------------------ (4)  (3) - (4) : -13\u03b2 = 26  \u03b2=26-13 = -2  Using (1), 5\u03b1 - (-2) = 17  5\u03b1 + 2 = 17  5\u03b1 = 17 - 2  5\u03b1 = 15  \u03b1=155 = 3  \u03b1 = 3, b = -2  From r = \u03b1p + \u03b2q (given)  r = 3p - 2q  2q = 3p - r  q=3p-r2","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2016>9>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2016","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : INDICES AND LOGARITHMIC FUNCTIONS","question":"Without using mathematical tables or calculator,  evaluate3/2 log27 - 3log5&radic;5&nbsp;log0.6","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Given that:  3/2 log27 - 3log5&radic;5&nbsp;log0.6  log33 \u00d7 3/2 - log(51 \u00d7 512)3log 6/10  =log39/2 - log(53/2)3log3/5  =9/2 log3 - 9/2 log5log3/5  =9/2 (log3 - log3)log 3/5   =9/2 (log 3/5)log 3/5  =92or12","marks":"5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2016>9>b","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2016","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : LINEAR TRANSFORMATION","question":"Two linear transformations A and B in the Oxy plane, are defined by  A: (x, y) \u2192 (x + 2y, -x + y)  B: (x, y) \u2192 (2x + 3y, x + 2y)  i. Write down the matrices A and B  ii. Find the image of the point P(-2, 2) under the linear transformation A followed by B.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"i. xy\u2192x2y-xyisgiven  i.exy\u219212-11xy  which gives matrix  A=12-11  xy\u21922x3yx2y  i.exy\u21922312xy  which gives matrix  B=2312  Hence, the two matrices of transformation are  A=12-11,B=2312    ii.IfpointP(-2,2)=-22  So-22\u219212-11-22  =-2\u00d71+2\u00d72-2\u00d71+2\u00d71  =-2+42+2  =24followedby  24\u2192231224  =2\u00d72+4\u00d732\u00d71+4\u00d72  =4+122+8  =1610  Hence, the image of P(-2, 2) under the linear transformation A followed by B is (16, 10).","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2016>10>a>i","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2016","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : BINOMIAL THEOREM","question":"Write down the expansion of (1 + x)7 in ascending powers of x.    (Leaving the answer in three decimal places)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Whenx=3,y=sqr(2(3)+832  y=&radic;6+89&nbsp;=&radic;629&nbsp;  y = &radic;6.889&nbsp; = 2.625  and so.","marks":"3","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2016>10>a>ii","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2016","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : BINOMIAL THEOREM~~PURE MATHEMATICS : SEQUENCES AND SERIES","question":"Write down the expansion of (1 + x)7 in ascending powers of x.If the coefficients of the fifth, sixth and seventh terms in the expansion in 10(a)(i) form a linear sequence (A.P), find the common difference of the A.P.      (Leaving the answer in whole number -ab)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The coefficient of the 5th, 6th and seventh terms were 35, 24 and 7, then 21 to 35 must have same value as 7-21. Also 21-32= -14, Since the difference is the same then the numbers are in Arithmetic Progression and the common difference of the AP is -14.","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2016>10>b","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2016","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : APPLICATIONS OF THE DEFINITE INTEGRAL","question":"Using the trapezium rule with ordinates at 1, 2, 3, 4 and 5, calculate, correct to two decimal places,  \u222b61 &radic;(2x + 8x2)&nbsp;dx","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The table below shows all the values of y for the corresponding values of x  x12345y3.1622.4502.6252.9163.212  The graph of y = &radic;2x + 8x-2&nbsp;  scale: on x-axis, 3cm rep 1 unit  on y - axis, 3cm rep 1 unit    From the graph, area under the curve y = is appropriately equal to the areas of trapezia  ABJK + BCHK + CDGH + DEFG  =12(3.162+2.450)+  12(2.450+2.625)+  12(2.625+2.916)+  12(2.916+3.212) = 2.806 + 2.5375 + 2.7705 + 3.064 = 11.178  Hence, \u222b51 &radic;(2x + 8x-2)&nbsp;dx = 11.18 ( 2dp)","marks":"5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2016>11>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2016","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : PERMUTATION AND COMBINATIONS.","question":"If kP2 = 72, find the value of k.      (Leaving the answer in whole number b)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Given that,  kP2 = 72  k!(k-2)!=72  k(k-1)(k-2)!(k-2)=72  k2 - k = 12  k2 - k - 72 = 0  k2 - 9k + 8k - 72 = 0  k(k - 9) + 8(k - 9) = 0  k + 8 = 0 or k - 9 = 0  k = -8 or k = 9  But k cannot be negative  \u2234 k = 9","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2016>11>b","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2016","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : TRIGONOMETRY","question":"Solve the equation 2cos2\u03b8 - 5cos\u03b8 = 3, for 0\u00b0 \u2264 \u03b8 360\u00b0.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Given that:  2cos2\u03b8 - 5cos\u03b8 = 3  2cos2\u03b8 - 5cos\u03b8 - 3 = 0  Let cos\u03b8 = m  2m2 - 6m + m - 3 = 0  (2m + 1)(m - 3) = 0  2m + 1 = 0 or m - 3 = 0  m=-12(ascos\u03b8cannotbegreaterthan5)  Thuscos\u03b8=-12  \u03b8=cos-1(-12)=120\u00b0or240\u00b0  Hence, \u03b8 = 120\u00b0 or 240\u00b0","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2016>12>a>i","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2016","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : STATISTICS","question":"The table shows the distribution of marks scored by some students in a test.  Marks1-1011-2021-3031-4041-5051-6061-7071-8081-9091-100Number of students31741859711510164216  Construct a cumulative frequency table for the distribution.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2016>12>a>ii","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2016","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : STATISTICS","question":"The table shows the distribution of marks scored by some students in a test.  Marks1-1011-2021-3031-4041-5051-6061-7071-8081-9091-100Number of students31741859711510164216  Draw a cumulative frequency curve for the distribution.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2016>12>b>i","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2016","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : STATISTICS","question":"The table shows the distribution of marks scored by some students in a test.  {{[Marks|1-10|11-20|21-30|31-40|41-50|51-60|61-70|71-80|81-90|91-100][Number of students|3|17|41|85|97|115|101|64|21|6    Use the Curve to estimate the number of students who scored marks between 32 and 74","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Number of Students who scored marks from 0 to 32 is 75. Number of students who scored marks from 0 to 14 is 490. Hence, number of students who scored marks between 32 and W is approximately 490 - 75 = 415","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2016>12>b>ii","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2016","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : STATISTICS","question":"Use the Curve to estimate the pass mark, if 18% of he students failed.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"18% of the students men 18th percentile  Thus18W100=18\u00d7550100 = 99th mark = 35.5 marks","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2016>12>b>iii","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2016","type":"Theory","sub_label":"iii","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : STATISTICS","question":"Use the Curve to estimate the lowest mark for distinction, if 8% of the students passed with distinction.    (Leaving the answer in whole number ab)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"If 8% of the student passed with distinction, then 92% of the students passed with a grade below distinction. Thus, 92nd percentile  =92\u00d7550100=506thmark  \u2234 77 marks  Hence, the lowest mark for distinction was 77 marks.","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2016>13>a>i","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2016","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : PERMUTATION AND COMBINATIONS.","question":"Two different Mathematics books, 5 different Physics books and 3 different Chemistry books are to be arranged on a shelf. How many arrangement are possible if books on the same subject must stand together?    (Leaving the answer in whole number abcd)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Given that:  M = m1m2 represent the mathematics books,  P = P1P2P3P4P5 represent the Physics books,  C = C1C2Cg represent the chemistry books.  If books on the same subject must stand together, then the following arrangements are possible  MPC, MCP, CMP, CPM, PMC, PCM, i.e 6 ways  M1M2 can be arranged in 2! ways   P1P2P3P4P5 can be arranged in 5! ways C1C2C3 can be arranged in 3! ways.  Altogether, there will be 6 \u00d7 2! \u00d7 5! arrangements i.e 6 \u00d7 2 \u00d7 5 \u00d7 4 \u00d7 3 \u00d7 2 \u00d7 1 = 8640 arrangements if books on the same subject must stand together.","marks":"3","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2016>13>a>ii","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2016","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : PERMUTATION AND COMBINATIONS.","question":"Two different Mathematics books, 5 different Physics books and 3 different Chemistry books are to be arranged on a shelf. How many arrangement are possible if only the Physics books must stand together?    (Leaving the answer in whole number abcde)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"If only the Physics books must stand together, than the other books can be arranged (as shown below) in 5! ways, since they are distinguishable.  \u2193M1\u2193M2\u2193C1\u2193C2\u2193C3\u2193  After this has been accomplished, the Physics books can be placed in the spaces marked \u2193 in 6ways.  The physics books can be arranged together in 5! ways since they are distinguishable.  Altogether, there will be 5! \u00d7 6 \u00d7 5! arrangements = 120 \u00d7 6 \u00d7 120 = 86400 arrangements if only the Physics books must stand together.","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2016>13>b","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2016","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : PROBABILITY","question":"In a certain community, 13 out of every 20 persons speak English. If 8 persons are selected at random from the community, find, correct to three significant figures, the probability that at least 3 of them speak English.    (Leaving the answer in three decimal places)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Let:  P denote probability of selecting a person from the community who speaks English  =1320=0.65  q denotes probability of selecting a person from the community who does not speak English 1 - 0.65 = 0.35  Then by the binomial probability distribution (p + q)8 = P8 + 8C1P7q1 + 8C2P6q2 + 8C3P5q3 + 8C4P4C4 + 8C5P3q3 + 8C6P2q6 + 8C7P1q7 + q8  Hence, the probability of selecting at least 3 out of 8 persons who speak English is given by  8C5P3q5 + 8C4P4q4 + 8C3P5q3 + 8C2P6q2 + 8C1P7p1 + p8 = 1 - {8C5P2q6 + 8C7P1q7 + q8} = 1 - {28(0.65)2(0.35)6 + 8(0.05)(0.35)7 + (0.35)8}  Pr = 1 - {28 \u00d7 0.4225 \u00d7 0.00184 + 8 \u00d7 0.65 \u00d7 0.000643 + 0.0001786}  Pr = 1 - (0.02177 + 0.00334 + 0.000180)  Pr = 1 - 0.02529  Pr = 0.975 (3.s.f)","marks":"5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2016>14>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2016","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : VECTORS","question":"Four vectors r = \u03b1i + \u03b2j where \u03b1 and \u03b2 are positive constants, s = 2I - j, m = 3I + 2j and n = i + j are such that the magnitude of r is three times as s and is parallel to the vector (m - n).  Find the values of \u03b1 and \u03b2.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"/r/ = 3/s/  &radic;\u03b12 + \u03b22&nbsp; = &#179&radic;22 + (-1)2&nbsp;  &radic;\u03b12 + \u03b22&nbsp; = &#179&radic;4 + 1&nbsp;  &radic;\u03b12 + \u03b22&nbsp; = &#179&radic;5&nbsp;  Take the square of both sides  \u03b12 + \u03b22 = 9 \u00d7 5  \u03b12 + \u03b22 = 45 --------------------------- (1)  m - n = (3i + 2j) - (i + j)   m - n = 3i + 2j - i - j = 2i + j  Thus, 2i + j = k(\u03b1i + Bj)  where k is a constant that makes r and (m - n) equal, then 2i + j = ki + \u03b2kj  By comparison:  \u03b1k = 2  k=2\u03b1  \u03b2k = 1  k=1\u03b2  k = k  2\u03b2 = ---------- (2)  substitute 2\u03b2 for in (1)  (2\u03b2)2 + \u03b22 = 45  4\u03b22 + \u03b22 = 45  5\u03b22 = 45  \u03b22=455=9  &radic;\u03b22&nbsp; = &radic;9&nbsp;  \u03b2 = 3  Hence, \u03b1 = 6 and \u03b2 = 3","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2016>14>b","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2016","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : VECTORS","question":"Four vectors r = \u03b1i + \u03b2j where \u03b1 and \u03b2 are positive constants, s = 2I - j, m = 3I + 2j and n = i + j are such that the magnitude of r is three times as s and is parallel to the vector (m - n).  Calculate the magnitude and direction of (r - s).","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"r - s = (6i + 3j) - (2i - j)  r - s = 6i + 3j - 2i + j  r - s = 4i + 4j  /r - s/ = &radic;42+42&nbsp; = &radic;16+16&nbsp; = &radic;32&nbsp;  /r - s/ = 4&radic;2&nbsp;  The diagram shows the direction of (4i + 4j) in the x-y plane    Let \u03b8 denote the direction of (r - s) from the +x axis   Thentan\u03b8=49=1  Thus \u03b8 = tan - 1(1) = 45\u00b0. Hence, the magnitude of (r - s) is 4&radic;2&nbsp; in the direction of 45\u00b0 the +x - axis.","marks":"5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2016>15>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2016","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : PROJECTILES","question":"A particle is projected vertically upward from the ground with speed 30ms-1. Calculate the maximum height reached by the particle.    (Leaving the answer in whole number ab)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Using v2 = u2 + 2gs  i.e 02 = 302 - 2 \u00d7 10 \u00d7 s  0 = 900 - 20\u00d7s  20 \u00d7 s = 900  s=90020  S = 45m  Hence, maximum height reached by particle is 45m.","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2016>15>b","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2016","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : PROJECTILES","question":"A particle is projected vertically upward from the ground with speed 30ms-1. Calculate the time taken by the particle to return to the ground.    (Leaving the answer in whole number b)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Using v = u + gt  i.e 0 = 30 - 10t  (upward motion)  10t = 30  t=3010=3s  Since the particle took 30 to reach the maximum height, it will also take 3s to return to the ground.","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2016>15>c","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2016","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"FINAL","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : PROJECTILES","question":"A particle is projected vertically upward from the ground with speed 30ms-1. Calculate the time(s) taken fo the particle to attain a height of 40m above the ground.  [Take g = 10ms-2]    (Leaving the answer in whole number b)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Using v2 = u2 + 2gs  i.e v2 = 302 - 2 \u00d7 10 \u00d7 40  v2 = 900 - 800  v2 = 100  v = &radic;100&nbsp;  v = 10ms-1  Thus, the particle was moving upward with a uniform speed of 10ms-1 at h = 40m above the ground.  So, using v = u + gt to find the time when V = 10ms-1  10 = 30 - 10t  10t = 30 - 10  10t = 20  t=2010  t = 2s  Hence, the particle took t = 2s to attain a height of 40m above the ground.","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"}];